John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Independent schools in Scotland have maintained a reputation for academic excellence, which continued in 2018 with another excellent test performance, which was only reinforced by individual and collective achievements in sport, the arts, music and other social sciences.
With up to 30,000 pupils across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Independent Schools Association (SCIS), strive to offer the best possible level of education to their pupils and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for their further education, their chosen career and their place in a global world.
As an education sector that can design and implement a personalized curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be a popular and desirable subject in schools.
Nelson Mandela said this: "If you speak to someone in a language they understand, your words reach them.
But if you speak his language, you touch his heart.
This is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely on English alone when we want to build relationships and trust with the people of other countries.
From this year's test results, we can see that languages are at the top with the highest scores for independent schools.
A total of 68% of pupils who studied foreign languages achieved a high A grade.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72% of pupils achieved an A in Chinese, with the same score being achieved by 72% of those studying German, 69% of those studying French and 63% of those studying Spanish.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland are recognising foreign languages as vital skills that children and young people will definitely need in the future.
Currently, languages as a subject of free choice by pupils are treated the same as natural and mathematical subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) both in the programmes of independent schools and beyond.
A 2014 survey by the UK Employment and Work Skills Commission showed that 17% cited insufficient language skills as one of the reasons why employers have difficulty finding employees.
Therefore, the command of foreign languages is increasingly becoming a requirement to prepare young people for their future careers.
More and more jobs require foreign language proficiency, making these skills essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the career you choose, if you master a foreign language, you will have a real advantage in the future, since you will have a lifelong mastery of that skill.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically puts the multilingual person one step ahead of the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4000 UK adults in 2013, 75% did not have a foreign language proficiency good enough to be able to speak a language, with French being the only language with a double-digit proficiency rate of 15%.
That's why investing in language learning today is important for children today.
Multilingualism, especially in developing economies, will give children a better chance of finding good jobs.
In Scotland, every school will be different from the languages taught.
A number of schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages that are considered more important to the UK in the future by 2020, such as Chinese or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interests, there will always be plenty of languages to choose from in independent schools, with teachers who are experts in their field.
Independent schools in Scotland are determined to provide an educational environment that will prepare children and give them the skills they need to succeed in life, no matter what the future holds.
There is no denying that in a global business environment, languages continue to play an incredibly important role for the future of any country, which requires that they be taken into account in the education system.
And really, modern languages should really be considered as "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, along with diversity and excellence, to young people in Scotland.
It must be done.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Independent Schools Association.
