North Korea says there's no way to unilaterally disarm without trust
North Korea's foreign minister told the UN on Saturday that continued sanctions deepened mistrust of the United States and there was no way the country could give up its nuclear weapons unilaterally under such circumstances.
At the annual general meeting of the world body, Ri Yong-ho said that in the past year, "significant measures of goodwill" have been taken, such as stopping nuclear and missile tests, destroying the nuclear test site and promising not to proliferate nuclear weapons and technology.
"However, we do not see a corresponding response from the United States", he said.
"Without trust in the United States, we will not believe in our own national security, and under no circumstances will we be the first to unilaterally disarm".
While Ri expressed North Korea's well-known complaints about Washington's resistance to a "phased" approach to denuclearization, in which North Korea would be rewarded for taking step-by-step measures, his statement seemed meaningful because he did not reject unilateral nuclear disarmament as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri cited a joint statement by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at the first summit between the US president and the North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim promised to work for the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula, and Trump gave assurances on North Korea's security.
North Korea has been pushing for an official end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the U.S. says Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls for the lifting of the tough international sanctions against North Korea.
The US is insisting on "demolition of nuclear weapons first" and increasing pressure through sanctions to achieve its goal through force, and even objecting to the "declaration of the end of the war", Ri said.
The idea that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a meaningless dream for those who don't know us.
The problem is that the continuing sanctions are deepening our distrust".
Ri did not mention whether a second meeting between Kim and Trump was planned, which the US leader stressed at the UN earlier this week.
Instead, the minister focused on the three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in in the last five months, adding: "If the country on the issue of nuclear disarmament was South Korea, not the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula would not have come to such a standstill".
However, the tone of Ri's speech was significantly different from the previous year when he told the UN General Assembly that North Korean missiles aimed at the US mainland were inevitable after angry President Trump called Kim a "suicide missile man".
At the UN this year, Trump, who last year threatened North Korea with "total destruction", praised Kim for his courage in taking disarmament measures, but said there was still much work to be done and sanctions should remain in place until North Korea removed its nuclear weapons.
On Wednesday, Trump stressed that there was no deadline for this, saying, "It doesn't matter if it takes two years, three years or five months".
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its actions.
However, US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday that: The implementation of the Security Council sanctions must continue until complete, final and confirmed nuclear disarmament is achieved.
The Security Council has unanimously tightened sanctions against North Korea since 2006 in an attempt to stop funding Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
