Harvard students on a course for adequate rest
A new course at Harvard University this year is getting all students to sleep more in an effort to combat the growing culture of all-night caffeinated learning.
One teacher found that students at the world's top university often don't even think about the basics of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Keisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, has developed a course he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after he talked about the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
Finally, a girl came to me and said, "Why are they telling me this now, in my senior year?"
She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me", he told The Telegraph.
The course, which is being held for the first time this year, teaches students the most important lesson about how good sleep habits help academic and athletic achievement, as well as improving overall well-being.
Paul Barrera, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after it was found that students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
One part is a room in a dormitory where students click on coffee cups, curtains, jogging shoes, and books to explain the effects of caffeine and light, how sports performance is affected by lack of sleep, and the importance of a bedtime routine.
Another section tells participants how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
Then a campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
We know that this isn't going to change the behavior of the students immediately.
But we believe they have a right to know just as you have a right to know the health effects of your choice to smoke, added Professor Keisler.
The culture of pride in studying all night is still there, he says, adding that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students mean that sleep deprivation is a growing problem.
Providing adequate and quality sleep should be the students' "secret weapon" in combating stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he says, even in order to avoid fullness, since sleep deprivation puts the brain into a hunger mode that makes them hungry all the time.
Raymond Saw, a 19-year-old California student studying chemistry and physical biology, helped Professor Keisler prepare the course by taking one of his classes during his first year at Harvard.
He says the course has "opened his eyes" and inspired him to spread it throughout the campus.
It is hoped that the next step will be for all graduates to be asked to complete a similar programme of study before joining the competing institution.
Professor Keisler recommends that students consider setting a bedtime and wake-up alarm and be aware of the harmful effects of "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED lighting, which can disturb circadian rhythms and lead to sleep problems.
