Tom Daly felt inferior because of his sexuality.
Olympic diver Tom Daly says he grew up feeling inferior to everyone else because of his sexuality, but that's what motivated him to succeed.
The 24-year-old athlete claims that until he started high school, he didn't realize that "not everyone is like me".
In an interview for the first edition of Desert Island Discs on Radio 4, hosted by Lauren Laverne, he spoke about gay rights to give "hope" to others.
He also said that when he became a parent, he became less interested in winning the Olympics.
The longtime host of the show, Kirsty Young, has been hospitalized for several months.
When he first appeared on Laverne Daily, he said he felt "less than everyone else" as he grew up, because it was not socially acceptable to like both girls and boys.
He said, "To this day, the feeling of being inferior and being different are actually the things that give me the energy and the strength to succeed".
He wanted to prove he was something, he said, so he wouldn't disappoint anyone when he eventually found out about his sexuality.
The two-time Olympic bronze medallist has become an active participant in LGBT campaigns and used his participation in this year's British Commonwealth Games in Australia to call for more countries to decriminalize homosexuality.
He said he did it because he was happy to be able to live in the open without consequences and wanted to inspire hope in others.
The three-time world champion said that when he fell in love with a man - the American filmmaker Dustin Lance Black, whom he met in 2013 - it was a surprise.
Daly married the Oscar winner, who is 20 years his senior, last year, but claims the age difference was never a problem.
"When you go through so much at such a young age", he said, "he competed in his first Olympics at 14 and his father died of cancer three years later". He said, "It's hard to find anyone your age who has experienced such ups and downs".
They became parents in June and have a son named Robert Ray Black-Daley, and Daley himself says his whole worldview has changed.
"If you had asked me last year, I would have told you that I was only interested in winning a gold medal", he said.
You know, there are more important things than Olympic gold medals.
My Olympic gold medal is Robbie.
His son was named after his father Robert, who died in 2011 at the age of 40 after being diagnosed with brain cancer.
Daly said his father couldn't accept that he was going to die, and one of the last things he asked was if they had tickets for the 2012 London Olympics, because he wanted to be on the front row.
"I couldn't tell him you weren't going to be next to me, Dad, or in the front row", he said.
"I held his hand until he stopped breathing, and at that moment, when I realized he was dead, I finally admitted that he wasn't invulnerable", he said.
The following year, Daly competed in the 2012 Olympics and won a bronze medal.
"I just knew that all my life I'd been dreaming of jumping in front of an Olympic crowd back home, and it was the greatest feeling", he said.
It also inspired his choice of the first song   Proud by Heather Small which accompanied him during his preparation for the Olympics and still makes him shudder.
Desert Island Discs is broadcast on BBC Radio 4 on Sundays from 11:15am, UK summer time.
