Germany again postpones the launch of a new warship
The German Navy's newest frigate was supposed to be commissioned in 2014 to replace the outdated Cold War-era battleships, but that won't happen until at least next year due to faulty systems and skyrocketing costs, local media reported.
The commissioning of the Rheinland-Pfalz, the flagship of the brand's new Baden-Wuerttemberg-class frigates, has been postponed until the first half of 2019, according to Die Zeit newspaper, which quoted an army spokesman as saying.
The vessel was due to join the Navy in 2014, but problems that arose after its delivery affected the fate of the ambitious project.
The four Baden-Wuerttemberg-class vessels, ordered by the fleet in 2007, will replace the obsolete Bremen-class frigates.
Understandably, they will have a powerful cannon, a range of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles, and some stealth technologies, such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic signals.
Other important characteristics include longer maintenance periods  the newest frigates must be able to be used for up to two years before returning to home ports.
But the continuing delays mean that the advanced warships  that are said to allow Germany to demonstrate power overseas  will be obsolete by the time they enter service, notes Die Zeit.
The ill-fated F125 made headlines last year when the German Navy officially refused to commission the vessel and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This is the first time the Navy has returned a ship to a shipbuilder after delivery.
Little is known about the reasons for the return, but German media have cited a number of major "software and hardware defects" that make the warship unusable if sent on a combat mission.
The software flaws are particularly important as the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class vessels will be operated by a crew of around 120 seamen  only half the crew of the older Bremen-class frigates.
In addition, the ship was found to be significantly overloaded, which reduced its efficiency and limited the ability of the Navy to add future upgrades.
The 7,000-tonne Rhineland-Palatinate is thought to be twice as heavy as the similar class of ships used by the Germans during World War II.
In addition to the defective hardware, the cost of the whole project  including for training of the crew  also becomes a problem.
It is estimated to have reached a staggering â¬3.1 billion ($3.6 billion)  from the initial â¬2.2 billion.
The problems with the latest frigates are becoming particularly important in light of recent warnings that Germany's naval forces are shrinking.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the German parliament's defense committee, admitted that the navy is actually running out of ships capable of carrying out missions.
The official said the problem has grown over time as old ships are decommissioned but no new ones are provided.
He complained that none of the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class frigates could be incorporated into the fleet.
The National Trust is monitoring the secret life of bats
A new study conducted on a farm in the Scottish Highlands aims to find out how bats use the landscape when they hunt.
The hope is that the findings will shed new light on the behavior of the unique flying mammals and help guide future conservation efforts.
The study by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland will follow the common bats as well as the brown arrowholes water nightingales at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed at key locations on the farm to track the bat's activities during the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using handheld detectors.
Expert sound analysis of all the recordings will determine the frequency of the call sounds of the bats, as well as the species they make.
A habitat map and a report will then be drawn up to create a detailed landscape picture of their behaviour.
Rob Duar, conservation adviser for the NTS, hopes the results will reveal which habitat areas are most important to bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help to determine the benefits of habitat management work, e.g. the creation of grasslands, and how best to maintain forest areas for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and Britain as a whole have declined dramatically over the past century.
They are threatened by construction activities that affect their shelter and lead to habitat loss.
Populations may be at risk from wind turbines and lighting, aircraft and certain chemical treatments of building materials, as well as attacks by domestic cats.
In fact, bats are not blind.
However, because of their night-time hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use advanced echolocation techniques to detect insects and obstacles along their flight path.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, takes bats very seriously.
The Trust has trained experts who conduct regular surveys, inspections of shelters and sometimes rescue operations.
The organisation has even set up Scotland's first and only special bat reserve at Threave Manor in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
The manor manager, David Thompson, says it's the perfect territory for them.
"Here in Threave, we have great ground for bats", he noted.
We have old buildings, very old trees and perfectly suitable habitat.
But there's a lot more to the bat that we don't know, so the work we're doing here and on other properties will help us better understand what they need to thrive.
It stresses the importance of bat checks before any property maintenance activities are undertaken, as the accidental destruction of a shelter can kill up to 400 female and young bats and destroy an entire local population.
Bats are a protected species and it is illegal to kill, harass, disturb or destroy their habitat.
Elizabeth Ferrell, a Scottish official with the Bat Conservation Trust, urged the public to help.
She said, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats and a lot of our animal species, because we just don't know what's happening to their populations".
