The Burnaston plant  where the Auris and Avensis models are produced  produced nearly 150 000 cars last year, 90% of which were exported to the rest of the European Union.
"My view is that if the UK leaves the EU at the end of March, production at our plant will stop", said Marvin Cook, Toyota's director in Burnaston.
Other UK carmakers, including Honda, BMW and Jaguar Land Rover, expressed concerns about leaving the EU without a deal and how cross-border trade would work.
BMW, for example, are saying they're closing their Mini factory in Oxford for a month after Brexit.
The main concerns of car manufacturers relate to the risks to the supply chain in the event of a no-deal Brexit.
Toyota's production line operates on the 'just in time' principle, with parts arriving every 37 minutes from suppliers from both the UK and the EU for the custom-built cars.
If the UK leaves the EU without a deal on March 29th, there could be problems at the border, which the industry says could lead to delays and parts shortages.
It would be impossible for Toyota to wait more than a day to replenish its inventory at the Darbyshire plant, the company said, and so production would stop.
Mr Clarke said Theresa May's 'chess' plan for the future relationship with the EU was 'precisely calibrated' to avoid these checks at the border.
