About 13 percent of newly built buildings in London are bought by people with non-British citizenship, which drives up prices and makes it difficult for first-time buyers to intervene in the property market.
Many of the affluent areas  especially in the capital  have become ghost towns because of the large number of foreign buyers who spend most of their time outside the country.
The new policy comes just weeks after Boris Johnson called for a reduction in the federal income tax to help more young people own their first home.
He accused the big construction companies of keeping property prices high by looting land but not using it, and asked Mrs May to abandon quotas for affordable housing to remedy Britain's housing shame.
Mr. Corbyn announced an attractive series of proposals for housing reform, including rent controls and an end to "no-fault" evictions.
He also wants to give councils more power to build new homes.
Mrs May said: "Last year I shared that I would like to devote my time as Prime Minister to rebuilding the British dream and making the lives of every new generation better.
