The summer heat has boosted the income of struggling British pubs, but it has added more stress to restaurant chains.
Pub and bar groups reported a 2.7 percent increase in sales in July, but restaurant revenue fell 4.8 percent, the statistics show.
Peter Martin from the business consultancy CGA, which compiled the statistics, said: "Due to the prolonged sunshine and longer than expected for England's World Cup, July follows a similar pattern to June, when pubs grew by 2.8 per cent, but restaurants took an even bigger hit.
The 1.8 percent drop in the restaurant business in June only deepened in July.
Pubs and liquor bars reported the best growth performance compared to the declining movement of restaurants.
Food bars also suffered from the sunshine, but not as much as restaurant owners.
Looks like people just wanted to go out and have a drink.
In pubs and bars, drinks sales jumped 6.6 percent for the month, while food sales fell 3 percent.
Paul Newman, from the leisure and entertainment analysts RSM, shared: "These results continue the trend we noticed at the end of April.
The timing and impact of major social or sporting events remain the biggest factors when it comes to sales in the out-of-home service sector.
It is not surprising that restaurant groups continue to suffer, although a decline in sales of 4,8% on an annual basis can be particularly painful in addition to the ongoing costs.
