Here are some basic facts about the Palu and Donggala Islands of Sulawesi:
Palau is the capital of Central Sulawesi province, located at the end of a narrow coastal strip on the western coast of Sulawesi Island, with a population of 379,800 in 2017.
The city was celebrating its 40th anniversary when it was hit by the earthquake and tsunami.
Donggala is a regency that stretches over 300 km (180 mi) along the coastline of Sulawesi Island.
The regency, which is an administrative region smaller than a province, had an estimated population of 299 200 in 2017.
Fishing and farming are the mainstays of the economy of Central Sulawesi province, especially in the coastal area of Dongola.
Nickel mining is also important for the province, but is concentrated mainly in Morava, on the opposite shore of Sulawesi.
Palu and Donggala have been hit by several tsunamis in the past 100 years, according to the Indonesian Disaster Recovery Agency.
In 1938, a tsunami killed more than 200 people and destroyed hundreds of buildings in Donggala.
A tsunami also hit the western part of Dongola in 1996, killing nine people.
Indonesia is located on the seismic "Pacific Ring of Fire" and is regularly hit by earthquakes.
Here are some of the major earthquakes and tsunamis in recent years:
2004: A strong earthquake on December 26 on the west coast of the Indonesian province of Aceh in North Sumatra triggered a tsunami wave that hit 14 countries and killed 226,000 people along the entire coastal strip of the Indian Ocean, more than half of them in Aceh.
2005: A series of powerful earthquakes hit the west coast of Sumatra in late March and early April.
Hundreds died on the island of Nias off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: A 6.8 magnitude rabbit lands Indonesia's most populous island, Java, triggering a tsunami that crashed into the southern coast, killing nearly 700 people.
2009: A 7.6 magnitude earthquake struck near the city of Padang, the capital of West Sumatra Province.
More than 1,100 people were killed.
2010: A 7.5 magnitude earthquake rocks one of the Mentawai Islands and triggers a 10-meter tsunami that destroys dozens of villages and kills about 300 people.
2016: A shallow earthquake hits the Pidi Jaya regency in Aceh, causing devastation and panic as people remember the devastation from the deadly 2004 earthquake and tsunami.
This time, the tsunami did not activate, but more than 100 people were killed by collapsed buildings.
2018: Severe earthquakes hit the tourist island of Lombok in Indonesia, killing more than 500 people, most of them on the northern side of the island.
The quake destroyed thousands of buildings and left thousands of tourists temporarily stranded.
