Red tide news: Concentrations are down in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota.
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a substantial decrease in red tide concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the Committee, there are reports of conditions for a breakdown in growth in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties  this shows a reduction in concentrations.
The red tide floodplains extend approximately 130 miles along the coast, from Pinellas County in the north to Lee County in the south.
Algae patches can be seen 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but they're smaller than last week.
Red tide is also being observed in Pasco County.
Over the past week, there have been reports of moderate concentrations in the coastal zone or slightly inland in Pinellas County, low to high concentrations on the coast of Hillsborough County, high concentration conditions in Manatee County, high concentration conditions on the coast or further inland in Sarasota County, moderate concentration conditions in Charlotte County, high concentration conditions on the coast or further inland in Lee County, and low concentrations in Collier County.
There are continuing reports of respiratory infections in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No reports of respiratory infections in northwest Florida in the past week.
